<p><b>Lawrence Henry "Larry" Summers</b> (born November 30, 1954) is an American <a href="/wiki/Economist" title="Economist">economist</a> and the Director of the White House's <a href="/wiki/National_Economic_Council" title="National Economic Council">National Economic Council</a> for President <a href="/wiki/Barack_Obama" title="Barack Obama">Barack Obama</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-change.gov_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-change.gov-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> Summers is the Charles W. Eliot University Professor at <a href="/wiki/Harvard_University" title="Harvard University">Harvard University</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Kennedy_School_of_Government" title="Kennedy School of Government" class="mw-redirect">Kennedy School of Government</a>. He is the 1993 recipient of the <a href="/wiki/John_Bates_Clark_Medal" title="John Bates Clark Medal">John Bates Clark Medal</a> for his work in several fields of economics and was <a href="/wiki/United_States_Secretary_of_the_Treasury" title="United States Secretary of the Treasury">Secretary of the Treasury</a> for the last year and a half of the <a href="/wiki/Presidency_of_Bill_Clinton" title="Presidency of Bill Clinton">Bill Clinton administration</a>. Summers also served as the 27th <a href="/wiki/President_of_Harvard_University" title="President of Harvard University">President</a> of <a href="/wiki/Harvard_University" title="Harvard University">Harvard University</a> from 2001 to 2006. Summers resigned as Harvard's president in the wake of controversy over a talk in which he speculated that women may statistically have lesser aptitude for work in the highest levels of math and science. Summers has been criticized by some liberals for the centrist economic policies he advocated as Treasury Secretary and in later writings.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
